measure_success: Look at various data streams

1. All students are succeeding academically, and are on track to graduating on time and ready for college.  - Students' subject area performance indices in math, reading, and science, as judged by the SAT and NGSS-aligned science assessments. - The percentage of students approaching and reaching the college ready bar on the SAT, and in particular progress toward this measure, as judged by PSATs, junior SAT performance, and SAT senior performance. - The percentage of students who meet and exceed growth projections on MAP assessments, with a focus on the lowest quartile, and who meet the college ready threshold on MAP. - The percentage of students earning enough credit to advance to the next grade, and who do not fail any of the core academic subjects -- with a particular focus on 9th grade and 10th grade performance. - The percentage of the graduation cohort successfully completing Integrated Math 2 and college-ready English courses (earning a C+ or higher). - The percentage of classroom observations, student survey responses, and curriculum evaluations that demonstrate strong evidence of high levels of rigor, relevance, relationships, and real roles and rights, using common rubrics.  - The percentage of students graduating in four years and six years. - The percentage of students who persist at Common Ground year to year -- and the reasons for students' departures. - The percentage of students who pass all four sections of the CT physical fitness assessment. - The percentage of students who participate in arts courses. - The average attendance rate, and percentage of individuals who are chronically absent.  Data will be disaggregated by race/ethnicity, grade (with a particular emphasis on 9th grade performance), free/reduced lunch status, gender, ELL, and SPED whenever possible and logical.  2. Common Ground engages a genuinely diverse community, and works unrelentingly toward equitable opportunities and outcomes for these students.  - The number of students applying to become students at Common Ground, the percentage who are offered and who accept placement, and the racial, gender, and geographic diversity of these applicants. - The percentage of Common Ground's student body who are students of color, qualify for free/reduced lunch, are English Language Learners, qualify for special education supports, and come from the City of New Haven. - The percentage of parents, students, and teachers rating school climate positively, measured by a climate survey correlated with New Haven district-wide survey and including questions on inclusiveness and equity. - The retention rate for classroom teachers, school staff, and school leaders, disaggregated by race. - The percentage of our staff, teaching corps and school/organizational leaders who are people of color. - The percentage of our teachers who demonstrate proficiency, according to school-wide teacher evaluation model (including observations, student assessments, school climate). - The per pupil expenditure at Common Ground High School; the percentage of this expenditure that comes from public funding. - The percentage of students who are suspended by race, gender, and socioeconomic status, compared to the composition of Common Ground as a whole. - The comparative academic achievement of significant subgroups -- by race, gender, socioeconomic status, and special education status -- with a particular focus on academic performance, graduation rates, and college matriculation.  3. All students are growing into powerful leaders for a just & sustainable environment.  - The percentage of our students who demonstrate mastery of our school-wide leadership standards, as measured by completion and successful defense of their leadership portfolios (pass/high pass), and by interim benchmarks at each grade level. - The percentage of Common Ground courses that include significant opportunities for environmental learning and leadership, aligned with school-wide leadership standards. - The percentage of our students who express interest in pursuing a field related to environment, health, sustainability or social justice in college. - The percentage of students engaged in sustained, substantive leadership opportunities in and outside of academic classes -- as demonstrated through their leadership portfolios. - The percentage of students who show growth in leadership confidence, self-efficacy, commitment to change-making, and ability to integrate environmental and social issues, as demonstrated by surveys developed in partnership with external evaluation partners.   Data will be disaggregated by race, free/reduced lunch status, gender, ELL, and SPED where numbers make this significant.  4. All students make successful transitions to learning and leadership beyond high school.  - The percentage of Common Ground students who will be first generation college students. - The percentage of students who visit colleges, and participate in college information sessions, by grade - The number and percentage of students who take on college-level and career-ready experiences during high school (AP courses, dual enrollment, Green Jobs Corps, credit-bearing internships), by grade level, and the % who demonstrate mastery in these learning opportunities (earning 3 or higher on AP exams, earning credit in college courses, successfully completing and demonstrating career, learning, and leadership skills in job placements and internships).  - The percentage of seniors who apply and are accepted to 2-year colleges, 4-year colleges, or other appropriate post-high school education programs. - The percentage of seniors who complete the FAFSA, and who receive merit-based scholarships. - Number of interactions with families around the college-going progress; percentage of families engaged in college access work. - The percentage of graduates who make successful transitions into the military, or into paid employment, after graduation. - The percentage of graduates who matriculate in 2-year colleges, 4-year colleges, or other appropriate post-high school education programs in the year after high school graduation. - The percentage of graduates who persist into their second year of college. - The percentage of graduates who earn a college degree within 2, 4 & 6 years. - The percentage of graduates engaged in community leadership roles (e.g., giving volunteer time), making financial contributions, and/or engaging in alumni network activities. - The percentage of students pursuing a career or college major related to Common Ground's environmental and social justice mission.  Data will be disaggregated by race/ethnicity, first generation college student status, free/reduced lunch status, gender, ELL, and SPED where numbers make this significant.  5. Common Ground's impact grows on and beyond our campus.  - The number of students enrolled at Common Ground High School. - Improvements in the physical and natural learning environment made.  - The number of capacity-building opportunities created for other schools and communities, the number of participants, and the duration of their engagement. - The percentage of participants who report that their experiences with Common Ground were engaging and relevant, who report new knowledge or understanding, who build new skills or capacity as a result of their experience, and who plan to act differently as a result of their experiences. - The percentage of participants who can demonstrate changes in practice, at the individual and school level, resulting from these opportunities. - Evidence of educational change resulting from Common Ground’s work with other schools, documented through interviews with school leaders and school case studies. - The number of students whose education is impacted by these changes in practice and capacity. - Evidence that students grew as learners and leaders as a result of these changes in practice and capacity.

We measure the success of our school model by: Growth/demand - Are programs full and/or on a waitlist? Student/family attrition - Are families happy? Is school attrition less than national average for private schools? Positive school family culture - Are families engaged and participating in school opportunities? Are students able to share concerns and vision? Do stakeholders feel valued? Community impact - Have we contributed to the building of a healthy community in our place through tangible projects?
VGHS uses a number of data collection tools to monitor our success and evaluate how we are doing.
Graduation rate, staff, student, & family satisfaction (turnover rates & climate surveys), standardized tests
